text=:Category: PracticeCategory%0a:Expansion: Thinking in multiple languages while learning%0a:Author: VikramM%0a:Original: [[Articles.ThatMultilingualVoiceInYourHead…|ThatMultilingualVoiceInYourHead…]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.roochis|roochis]]%0a:Section: A%0a:Completed: 05.02.2021 - 17:00%0a:Status: ungraded%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aIn my personal experience learning a second language for several years, I remember at one time dealing with the new language by translating to English, formulating a response in English, and finally translating back to the other language and then speaking or writing. After a certain point (I'm not exactly sure exactly when), I remember just being able to think in the second language in class/whenever it was used around me and no longer doing the back and forth translation. It definitely made speaking/conversation much easier and faster. Something interesting is that the transition happened right around when the classes I was taking started focusing more on reading/listening to real media in that language rather than concentrating on more grammatical/structure oriented aspects. More on the topic of your question, I think that the language one thinks in can be dependent on what is being spoken around them. %0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a#foxbegin 210512-000938-922430#%0a!!Backup interface%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a#foxend 210512-000938-922430#
